node.text:
Look, I taught something!! 💪✨

The first week always feels like a hamster wheel of craze, but the second feels so much nicer. It’s day 6 and I’m finally starting to get into the groove of the new year. 
Favorites:
1️⃣ My freaking amazing team. Seriously such a dream and I feel grateful every single day. 
2️⃣ My kids, obviously. Their WEIRD is finally starting to shine through, and that’s when the year gets fun. 
3️⃣ DEPARTMENTALIZING!!! I can’t tell you how nice it is to teach only 2 subjects this year, especially after having a combo class last year. Last year felt like double-time, and this year feels so manageable and happy. 

I hope you all have the BEST start to your school years and that you’re able to find the glimmers in each day, as @hellomissromeo would say 🥰

Starting this year with these digital scavenger hunts for Google apps, because if I hear, “I lost my doc!” a million times again this year, I  might not make it 🤪

The ultimate goal in teaching is always to create a classroom space where every student feels safe, loved and free to be exactly who they are. Lauren from @simplystainedshop and I have teamed up again to bring you three new signs with this goal in mind. ✨

You belong. 
Your voice matters. Let it sing!
Let your light shine. 

We’re hosting the easiest giveaway to celebrate the new collection. To enter:
1. Make sure you’re following @simplystainedshop 
2. Tell us which sign you’d like for your classroom! 

That’s it!  We’ll pick a winner tomorrow morning and send the sign off ASAP so it’s ready to welcome your new class on the first day of school ✨

node.text:
Two. Days. Left. 

I feel like we’ve run the longest, hottest, up-hilliest race of our life this year and we can finally see the finish line. 

This has been the HARDEST year of our lives, but we did it. We’re freaking amazing for doing it, but I’m hoping (praying, pleading) we never have to do anything like this again. 

I’m going to miss this class so much (I cried 4 times today - see my stories if you’re interested in the details 🙈), but I’m SO READY for summer. I plan on soaking up every minute of this weekend, and then every minute of our last two days, and then I’m going to do absolutely nothing school related for a looooong time because my heart, mind and soul deserve a break 💗

Gorgeous lettering from the lovely @thebasiclifeofbrooke

node.text:
In honor of Mental Health Awareness Month and with the hope of continuing the mental health conversation, I’d love to share my experience 🤍

I’ve always had anxiety but didn’t necessarily know that’s what I was experiencing until a few years ago when I had a series of panic attacks at school (not surprising that they were triggered by school stress, eh?). I *thought* I could control it myself, but the racing heart, the sleepless nights and the endless worrying persisted until I broke down at dinner with a friend and called my doctor for help. I remember that desperate feeling so vividly. 

I’m lucky because the second medicine we tried has been the perfect fit. I still feel a bit of anxiety from time to time but it’s manageable and not overwhelming my life like it did before. 

After my dad died, however, I fell into a deeper hole of depression and anxiety than I’ve never experienced. I adopted the motto of faking it ‘til I make it so I could function at school, but when I got home at night, I would crash and cry myself to sleep. I’m SO INCREDIBLY THANKFUL for the people around me who support my mental health. Traumatic life events aren’t meant to be handled alone, and increasing my dose of medicine, in conjunction with other healthy habits, has helped me to manage my grief and feel like myself again. 

If you’re struggling with your mental health, I see you. I support you. I believe in you, and I’m here for you if you need to share your story. 🤍🤍🤍

Thank you to @stephkaydesigns for creating this beautiful image.

node.text:
Hi!

It’s been awhile. I’m slowly crawling out of a two-month-long dark hole. Turns out losing a parent affects everything in your life, and everything, even regular everyday tasks, suddenly feels impossible. 

I’ve been trying to force myself to do things that bring me happiness, even if I don’t want to, and it has helped so much. 

The other thing that has helped so much is the incredible people in my life, and that includes all of YOU. Thank you all for being gigantic mega-beams of light in my life. You’ve been so understanding when resources aren’t updated on time or when it’s taken me too long to respond, and I appreciate you all more than I’ll ever be able to ever be able to show you. 

🤍🤍🤍

node.text:
It breaks my heart to type this.  The most badass dad I've ever known passed away this weekend.  His 74-year-old heart just couldn't keep up with his 22-year-old ambition anymore. 

I recognize how lucky I am to have had such a loving and dedicated dad. He channeled his love of baseball into my love of soccer and became the best damn soccer dad in history.  He never missed a practice, game or opportunity to drive me all over the US to play, and when I grew up and soccer dwindled away, he was still my biggest fan, always the first to visit every time I moved, the first to help me anytime I needed it, even the first to like every teachergram post. I’m completely heartbroken and lost but have peace knowing he passed away doing something he loved. 

Since his passing, we've found the most incredible memories tucked away in a closet - hundreds of letters he wrote to his mom and brother while he was in the army.  They're hilarious and fascinating and have made us feel so much closer to him as we mourn.  We only wish we knew about these letters earlier so we could hear the stories behind them.

 💔
